<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-397-264  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 397 264.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>InTech  May 1989 v36 n5 p28(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Expert system aids process maintenance.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Myers, Richard C., Jr.; Hadley, Jeff.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Expert system-based workstations enable the acquisition and use ofexpert knowledge for the operation, diagnosis, maintenance, andrepair of process control systems.andP;  Process control downtime canseverely affect productivity, system operation and maintenancecosts, and profits.andP;  Fast evolving manufacturing technologiesdemand new training, documentation, and maintenance strategies tooptimize process control performance.andP;  The expert systemworkstation offers such optimizing capabilities as rapid problemdiagnosis, easily available system expertise, usabledocumentation, short and long term maintenance solutions, andlower training obligations and costs.andP;  A typical system includes aPC-based workstation, touch screen monitor, laserdisk- orCD-ROM-based system information, and expert system software.andP;  Thedevelopment cycle of a process control analysis workstation isdescribed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Expert SystemsProcess ControlSystems AnalysisApplicationsPerformance ImprovementWorkstations.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotographchart.andO;Caption:   How people interact with expert systems. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>